<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Energy and Climate Change Select Committee Inquiry - Heat</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by ICOM Energy Association (HOT40)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The ICOM Energy Association (ICOM) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">welcome</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the opportunity to respond to the Energy and Cli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mate Change Select Committee’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Inquiry into H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eat.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ICOM is the trade association, representing the Industrial and Commercial sectors of the Heating Industry and is made up from members who produce/market products used in that sector of the industry.  The majority of members are industr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ial and commercial boiler manufacturers, producing products which operate, in the main, on gas, oil and biomass fuels, although other fuels are used in specialist applications. ICOM also has the majority of packaged burner manufacturers as members, produci</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ng burners to work with the industrial and commercial boilers and operating on gas, oil and bio-fuels.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The equipment is used for the production of hot water and steam to be used in heating systems and for process installations.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ICOM members also market ren</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ewable products such as Heat Pumps, Combined Heat and Power (CHP), Solar Thermal and Solar PV.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Other ICOM members include manufacturers of Air and Radiant heaters, controls and water treatment products.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The ICOM members have an approximate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">annual </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sales of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">£300 – £350Million.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We would be happy to discuss any of the issues rais</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed in this response and in the I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nquiry with the Select Committee. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ndustry believes that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the carbon emission targets are achievable as long as clear policies a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nd support are given by Government.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The industrial/commercial sector needs to be treated differently to the domestic sector, due to the fact that the building structures vary so considerably and most installations are different, whereas domestic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">properties have similar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ly designed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">installations.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The domestic agenda is taking priority due to the large number of installations and the relative ease in controlling incentives. However, the industrial/commercial sector is a large user of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">energy and prod</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ucer of GHG and the industry believes that the overall efficiency of the installation plays a very large part in reducing t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he energy requirements and GHG emissions. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The industry believes that the route to achieving the necessary reductions in energy cons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">umption and GHG emissions needs mix of renewable energy products, working in conjunction with high efficiency gas and oil boilers.  The use of shale gas and bio-oil will help to reduce the carbon emissions. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Heat Demand</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Whereas in the domestic sector, there is a similarity of use and output from one property to another, in the industrial/commercial sector this is not the case.  There are a considerable number of different heat demands from simple heating of a small office</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to the heating of a large manufacturing complex. There are also process applications which can vary from supplying hot water for a factory process to high grade steam for an industrial process. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The variation of equipment design </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">installed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">contributes to t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he problems of determining how to approach the need for financial support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> required </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">interest the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">end </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">users in changing to a greener installation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The demand for heat is reducing as buildings and installations are being built or refurbished to higher stan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">dards.  The Building Regulations are regularly up-dated to bring the standards of building fabric and internal systems to a greater efficiency, thereby reducing energy requirements.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is important that there is an incentive to ensure that existing buildin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">g owners and operators do not take the easy route and decide not to refurbish the building and accept that energy usage and running costs are high.  The capital required to carry out the refurbishment is not always easy to obtain and this is a factor in de</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cisions made not to improve the structure.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Heat Generation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The industrial/commercial sector uses large amounts of energy, mainly gas and oil to generate the forms of heat required for the various types of use. Some of these processes are using very old equ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ipment in out of date applications. The costs of up-dating an industrial process can in some situations warrant the move to another part of the world, thereby causing a loss of UK jobs and a deficit in the balance of payments.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The variations in the types </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and grade of heat required in the industrial/commercial sector are extensive and this gives rise to great difficulty in using the renewable technologies.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> There are processes which will use a constant volume of hot water which could be ideal for a biomass b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oiler, CHP or heat pump which work more efficiently at a constant load, however, the temperature specified can also play a part in determining whether these renewable technologies will operate in the most efficient way.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The DECC Heat Strategy is a good bas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is for changing the industry perception to the way that heat is generated, however, the design concepts in the industrial/commercial sector are so varied that the basis of reducing fossil fuels usage to such a low percentage of heat generated will be extre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mely difficult to achieve.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The industrial/commercial industry accepts that renewable fuels will play a major part in reducing energy usage and GHG emissions. Manufacturers in this sector are developing products to maximise the use of renewable fuels. Howev</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">er, the technologies such as biomass, CHP and heat pumps, operate at their most efficient when they are delivering a steady heat load. Solar thermal products have a very intermittent supply of heat due to the vagaries of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">British weather.  The working t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">emperatures of each technology are different and trying to work outside those parameters tends to reduce efficiency.  The most energy efficient way to generate heat is to combine one or two renewable energy fuelled pieces of equipment working with a gas or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> oil boiler to give the top up when the demand increases. The addition of intelligent pumps and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">controls</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> will ensure that the renewable fuelled equipment will operate at a constant demand and the boilers will take the peak and instantaneous heat demands.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eat generation in industrial/commercial installations tends to vary over a very wide range dependent on usage and time of year and therefore the use of renewable technology to supply the base load with fossil </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fuelled</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> appliances acting in support will give </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the most fuel efficient operation with reduced GHG emission.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The use of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">thermal storage will also benefit the use of renewable technologies, due to the fact that it allows the renewable technologies to operate longer without cycling.  This is the most ene</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rgy efficient method of operation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Heat Waste</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Waste heat from CHP generators should be used to support the heating or process system.  There is a balance that needs to be made between the amount of electricity being generated and the amount of heat being p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">roduced. A bias towards the electrical generation could mean that there is a large amount of thermal energy being wasted and therefore a bias towards having a base thermal load and maybe generating a smaller amount of electricity can be the most energy and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> emission efficient answer. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">When a CHP installation is designed to utilise the waste heat, then a back up heat system will be required and the most versatile method is to use a high efficiency gas/oil fired condensing boiler.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Committee questions</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ICOM’s view on the Government’s approach is to reduce heat energy demand is supportive as we know the need to reduce energy usage and GHG emissions. However, we believe that a more balanced approach is needed, as the reliance on renewable energy technology</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and the production of green electricity is reducing the Government’s options. Renewable technology will obviously play a part in the process towards the 2050 targets, however, the use of green electricity and heat pumps as the main source of heat energy i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s questioned. The investment needed in re-building the electricity grid to enable the number of heat pumps required to operate is surely not viable. A balanced approach to include gas and oil products, working at peak efficiency with added emphasis on buil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ding and system improvements will, we believe, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">enable the targets to be achieved </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a more cost effective way.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We understand from information in the press, that the interim 2020 target will not be achieved and we would suggest that more information is prov</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ided, in some detail, to enable the manufacturers of industrial/commercial equipment to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">be able to determine the best way to develop their products range to assist in achieving those targets.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Biomass as a fuel is an important factor in achieving the energy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and emission reductions required by Government. The calculations of GHG is straight forward related to each appliance, however, trying to calculate the overall GHG savings within the industry is more difficult. The installations covered by the RHI scheme </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">obviously give a very accurate figure for emissions based on the kW hours claimed by the operator.  However, not all biomass boilers sold are being </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">subject to a RHI application due to the perception that the process is protracted and involves added expense</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of calibrated heat meters and in some instances, more expensive pipe work systems to conform to the criteria. Determining accurately the total kW hours would be the best way to determine the reduction in GHG, and therefore consideration should be given to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the complexity of the RHI process.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The sustainability issue with biomass fuel is covered adequately and the added criteria for RHI approval next year will ensure that the RHI approved installations will have to prove sustainability. The major wood pellet </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">manufacturers have set up their processes to use sustainable wood sources as they were aware of the pressures being brought by Government and the industry. However, there are a considerable number of installations using locally sourced wood from estates an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d these will be more difficult to manage. This is mainly the wood chip and logs side of the industry and sustainability is not always of prime importance. A method of policing these areas needs to be developed to ensure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that these installations are control</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">led in the same way as pellet manufacturers.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Environmental impact is not considered in the same way as reducing energy and GHG emissions. The renewable fuel technologies, in the main, do not operate cleanly when cycling.  When a biomass boiler is operated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with short cycles, the start up and shut down processes are more difficult to keep clean, therefore a more constant demand or the use of large thermal stores are needed to ensure that the boiler operates cleanly.  In some of the major cities in the UK, ext</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ra abatement is required to ensure that the emissions of particulates are virtually zero.  This has a cost implication to achieve these levels. The previous arguments for a balanced approach by using renewable fuel products backed up by fossil fuel product</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s to cover the peak demands, not only improves the energy efficiency, but also reduces emissions by allowing the biomass boiler to operate at a constant level. CHP engines work in a similar way, in that by allowing the engine to operate at a constant level</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, the start up and shut down cycles, which are the worst for emissions are reduced and therefore the emissions are kept to a minimum. Added to the direct emission reduction is the fact that constant running reduces the wear on the components in the engine </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">which also means that the performance is maintained.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The use of gas to directly provide space heating or any other form of energy use gives </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">flexibility</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to the ope</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ration of the system.  The gas </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fired equipment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as part of an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">installation is independent and t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">herefore is only used when the system has a demand. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, the demand for electricity to operate a heat </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pump is a much less exact science and the balanced approach of a combined heat pump and fossil fuelled boiler to give the most efficient package is pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oposed to even out the peak demands. The cost of up-grading the National Grid also needs to be added to the equation and  lower costs to give incentives to improving the efficiency of current installations would, we believe, be a better option.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The use of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">community heating systems or district heating schemes are not playing a major p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">art in the UK at present. ICOM suggests that Government support for this type of heating scheme would improve the use of these systems, especially in multiple occupancy installa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tions where there is a central boiler house using a biomass boiler with fossil fuel boiler back up and then using heat meters in each dwelling. This option would be more energy and emissions efficient than installing individual heat generators. This form o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f installation is widely used in Europe, but historically in the UK, there has been the principal of having individual heat generators and so there is the need to educate people to this different way of thinking. ICOM supports the use of district heating s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">chemes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The use of thermal storage, when used with renewable energy equipment should be promoted by Government to improve the operating process of that type of equipment. The addition of a thermal store has a cost implication and therefore is subject to th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e cos</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t analysis of the installation and in many cases is removed from the design to save money.  ICOM believes that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the use of thermal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">stores</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> improves the flexibility of the system and helps reduce energy use by reducing cycling of the heat generator.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusions</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ICOM supports the Government in it’s aim to reduce energy use and GHG emissions.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ICOM promotes the balanced approach to achieving the targets on energy and GHG emission reduction by using high efficiency gas &amp; oil boilers to work in conjunction</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with renewable energy equipment and intelligent pumps and controls to give the most efficient system design.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The use of the RHI should be expanded to include hybrid systems of renewable and fossil fuels which will help in achieving the reduction of energy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> use.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 7.1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>